ndo Shinkosha Publishing Co., Ltd. |location=Tokyo|language=Japanese|isbn=9784416716724|url=http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/product/NEOBK-2036444|ref={{Harvid|KPP|2016}}}}\n* {{Citation|author1=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu|date=January 21, 2017|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Atashi Idol Ja Shi!!! (TOKYO NEWS MOOK)|publisher=Tokyo News Service Co., Ltd.|location=Tokyo|language=Japanese|isbn=9784863366176|url=http://zasshi.tv/products/detail/HBTVB170121_001-00-00-00-00-00|ref={{Harvid|KPP|2017}}}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kyary Pamyu Pamyu}}\n* [http://kyary.asobisystem.com/english/ Official English-language website]\n* [http://japandaman.com/2014/03/22/interview-kyary-pamyu-pamyu/ Japandaman Kyary Australian Tour Eve Interview]\n* {{IMDb name|4994376|Kyary Pamyu Pamyu}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=teMdjJ3w9iM Kyary Pamyu Pamyu \u2013 Ninja Re Bang Bang \u2013 YouTube]\n* {{Youtube|user=kyarypamyupamyuTV|kyarypamyupamyuTV}}\n\n{{Kyary Pamyu Pamyu}}\n{{Capsule (band)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pamyu Pamyu, Kyary}}\n[[Category:Kyary Pamyu Pamyu| ]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Japanese synth-pop singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese female models]]\n[[Category:Japanese female pop singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese bloggers]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Sire Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Harajuku]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yasutaka Nakata]]\n[[Category:Women bloggers]]\n[[Category:Japanese women in electronic music]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               = Kyary Pamyu Pamyu\n| image              = Kyary Pamyu Pamyu 20120707 Japan Expo 01.jpg\n| caption            = Kyary Pamyu Pamyu performing at the [[Japan Expo]] in July 2012\n| native_name        = \u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085\n| birth_name         = {{nihongo|Kiriko Takemura|\u7af9\u6751 \u6850\u5b50}}\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1993|1|29}}<ref>[https://www.facebook.com/kyaryofficial kyary pamyu pamyu] (Official Facebook page)</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Nishit\u014dky\u014d, Tokyo|Tanashi, Tokyo]], Japan\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* model\n* blogger\n}}\n| height             = 157 cm (5 ft. 2 in.)\n| agent              = Asobisystem\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = [[J-pop]], [[Electronic dance music|EDM]], [[Techno music|techno]], [[synthpop]]\n| instrument = Vocals\n| years_active = 2010\u2013present\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Yasutaka Nakata]]\n* [[Charli XCX]]\n* [[Tempura Kidz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kawaii-matsuri.jp/eng/artist/261.php|title=TEMPURA KIDZ|work=KAWAii!! MATSURi Official Website|accessdate=April 25, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930170506/http://kawaii-matsuri.jp/eng/artist/261.php|archivedate=September 30, 2015}}</ref> <!--Please do not add any international artists here. She's only associated with Japanese music artists, not American music artists.-->}}\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[Unborde]]\n* [[Warner Music Group|Warner]]\n* [[Sire Records|Sire]]\n* Asobisystem (current)\n}}\n| website = {{URL|kyary.asobisystem.com}}\n}}\n| alias              = Caroline Charonplop Kyary Pamyu Pamyu;<br/>Kyary\n| origin             = <!--Do not add without a source-->\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Kiriko Takemura'''|\u7af9\u6751 \u6850\u5b50|Takemura Kiriko|born January 29, 1993}}, known professionally as '''Kyary Pamyu Pamyu''' ([[Hiragana]]: \u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085), is a Japanese singer, model, and blogger. Her public image is associated with Japan's ''[[kawaii]]'' and ''[[decora (style)|decora]]'' culture, centered in the [[Harajuku]] neighborhood of Tokyo,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tokyofashion.com/oh-my-god-harajuku-girl-by-kyary-pamyu-pamyu/|title=\"Oh! My! God! Harajuku Girl\" by Kyary Pamyu Pamyu}}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu's music is produced by musician [[Yasutaka Nakata]] of electronic music duo [[Capsule (band)|Capsule]].\n\nHer 2011 single \"[[Pon Pon Pon]]\" reached the top ten on Japan's [[Oricon Singles Chart|Oricon]] music chart; the 2012 singles \"[[Candy Candy (song)|Candy Candy]]\" and \"[[Fashion Monster]]\" followed this success. Pamyu Pamyu has since released four full-length albums: ''[[Pamyu Pamyu Revolution]]'' (2012), ''[[Nanda Collection]]'' (2013), ''[[Pika Pika Fantajin]]'' (2014), and ''[[Japamyu]]'' (2018).\n\nThough most of her success as a recording artist has been in Asia, she has also gained popularity in Western countries due in part to Internet videos which have gone [[Viral video|viral]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0000708084|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's success abroad: Warner Music Japan CEO discusses J-pop interest overseas}}</ref> Media outlets have referred to Pamyu Pamyu as \"Harajuku Pop Princess\", and she has been photographed for magazines such as ''[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused]]''.<ref name=\"KYARY PAMYU PAMYU COVERSHOOT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/15088/1/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-covershoot|title=KYARY PAMYU PAMYU COVERSHOOT| date = November 2012}}</ref> In 2013, she signed a distribution deal with [[Sire Records]] to release her material in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/mike-ragogna/conversations-with-seymou_b_4041162.html|title=Conversations With Seymour Stein, Lori Lieberman and Sun Records' Josh Collum, Collin Brace & Julie Roberts, Plus an Ed Kowalczyk Exclusive | work=HuffPost | first=Mike|last=Ragogna|date=October 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of February 2020, Kyary Pamyu Pamyu has sold over 970,000 physical albums and singles in Japan according to [[Oricon]] as well as over 2.25 million track downloads of all her singles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/542438/ranking/cd_album/|title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085\u306e\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u58f2\u308a\u4e0a\u3052\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 (''subscription only'')|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/542438/ranking/cd_single/|title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085\u306e\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\u58f2\u308a\u4e0a\u3052\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 (''subscription only'')|publisher=Oricon|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPamyu Pamyu was born on January 29, 1993 in [[Nishit\u014dky\u014d, Tokyo]], Japan. Throughout most of her childhood life, she was raised in a traditional strict household, where her parents frequently set early curfews and limited her cell phone access. Pamyu Pamyu's mother was very critical of her fashion sense to the point where she would have to leave the house dressed normally and change into [[Harajuku]]-style clothing inside a public restroom. Pamyu Pamyu often returned home and found that her mother had disposed of her fashion accessories, which led to further quarrels. She writes in her autobiography, ''Oh! My God!! Harajuku Girl'', that her father was more supportive of her, although they had their fair share of quarrels as well.<ref name=\"\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\">{{cite book|title=OH!MY GOD!! \u539f\u5bbf\u30ac\u30fc\u30eb|last=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc|first=\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085|date=|publisher=|isbn=9784591125427|location=|language=Japanese|trans-title=Oh! My God! Harajuku Girl|accessdate=}}</ref> She took dance lessons. Around the age of 12, she appeared in a video series called ''Seijun Imouto Club'' (\u6e05\u7d14\u3044\u3082\u3046\u3068\u5036\u697d\u90e8, lit. \"Innocent Sister Club\"), and in another titled ''Kasumi'', in which she was filmed posing while wearing a school-issued bathing suit among other things.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://product.rakuten.co.jp/search/4582108811864/ |title=\u3010\u697d\u5929\u5e02\u5834\u30114582108811864\u306e\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c \u2013 \u697d\u5929\u30d7\u30ed\u30c0\u30af\u30c8 |publisher=Product.rakuten.co.jp |accessdate=July 20, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223134848/http://product.rakuten.co.jp/search/4582108811864/ |archive-date=February 23, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2009\u20132010: Career beginnings===\nTakemura started as a fashion blogger, and then began her professional career as a model for [[Harajuku]] fashion magazines such as ''Kera!'' and ''Zipper''.<ref>[http://kyary.asobisystem.com/?page_id=7 Kyary Profile in Japanese and English]. Kyary.asobisystem.com. Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref> After achieving a measure of fame, she collaborated with the ''Eyemazing'' company to produce a line of fake eyelashes called \"Harajuku Doll\".<ref>[http://tokyofashion.com/harajuku-doll-eyelashes-eyemazing-kyary/ Harajuku Doll Eyelashes by Eyemazing x Kyary]. Tokyofashion.com. Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref>\n\nTakemura explained her stage name in a Japanese [[MTV]] interview. Wearing blonde wigs as a fashion affectation in high school, a friend began calling her \"Kyari\" because she embraced Western culture and seemed \"like a foreign girl\". The name stuck. Upon starting her blog, she felt the name \"Kyari\" \u2014 a phonetic Japanese spelling of the Western name \"Carrie\" \u2014 was too short, and \"missing something\". Takemura added \"Pamyu Pamyu\" because it sounded cute.<ref name=\"mtv\"/> She states her full stage name as {{nihongo|\"Caroline Charonplop Kyary Pamyu Pamyu\"|\u304d\u3083\u308d\u3089\u3044\u3093\u3061\u3083\u308d\u3093\u3077\u308d\u3063\u3077\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085|Kyarorain Charonpuroppu Kyar\u012b Pamyu Pamyu}}.<ref>[http://ameblo.jp/kyarypamyupamyu/entry-10687370517.html About Kyary \uff5cKyary Official Blog] Retrieved on 17 January 2012.</ref>\n\nTakemura first met [[Yasutaka Nakata]], the music producer of her favorite electropop group [[Perfume (Japanese band)|Perfume]], at his club event. Because he makes music for the fashion industry, he was intrigued by her career and encouraged her to debut as a singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mdpr.jp/news/detail/1332361 |title= \u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3001\u4eba\u751f\u3092\u5909\u3048\u305f\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u79d8\u8a71\u660e\u304b\u3059 |publisher=modelpress |date=February 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2011\u20132012: ''Moshi Moshi Harajuku'' and ''Pamyu Pamyu Revolution'' ===\nIn April 2011, along with Japanese fashion editor and photographer Yasumasa Yonehara and Japanese brand 6%DokiDoki, Pamyu Pamyu participated in the charity event \"One Snap for Love\" to benefit victims of the [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami]].<ref>[http://tokyofashion.com/one-snap-for-love-yone-kyary-pamyu-pamyu-harajuku/ Harajuku earthquake relief effort frontlining Kyary]. Tokyofashion.com (April 4, 2011). Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref> In July, she released her first promo single, \"[[PonPonPon|Pon Pon Pon]]\", citing [[Gwen Stefani]], [[Christina Aguilera]] and [[Katy Perry]] as inspirations at that time.<ref name=\"timeouttokyo\">{{cite web|last=Hadfield |first=James |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu: the long interview |url=http://www.timeout.jp/en/tokyo/feature/4760/Kyary-Pamyu-Pamyu-the-long-interview |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150516002617/http://www.timeout.jp/en/tokyo/feature/4760/Kyary-Pamyu-Pamyu-the-long-interview |archive-date=May 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |work=Time Out Tokyo |accessdate=November 8, 2016 |date=August 19, 2011 }}</ref> The music video, a psychedelic tribute to kawaisa and Decora culture, was released to YouTube and became a viral hit, leading to it being reported on by MTV and ''[[The Huffington Post]]''.<ref name=\"MTV\" /><ref name=\"Dooling\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/27/ponponpon-gives-us-a-kawa_n_911470.html|title='PonPonPon' Gives Us A Kawaisa Seizure | work=HuffPost | first=Annemarie|last=Dooling|date=July 27, 2011}}</ref> The single was produced by Yasutaka Nakata and is the first release from Pamyu Pamyu's debut album, ''[[Moshi Moshi Harajuku]]'', which was released August 17, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tokyofashion.com/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-ponponpon-music-video-6dokidoki/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu \"PonPonPon\" Music Video w/ Art by 6%DokiDoki}}</ref> \"Pon Pon Pon\" was released on July 20, 2011. The single entered ''Billboard'' Japan's Hot 100 chart at 72 on July 31, 2011.<ref name=\"jphot100-1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=hot100&year=2011&month=08&day=1|title=Billboard Japan Hot 100|date=August 1, 2011|website=|language=ja|access-date=November 12, 2016}}</ref> American rapper [[G-Eazy]] sampled \"Pon Pon Pon\" on his single \"Lost in Translation\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/g-eazy/lost-in-translation|title=G-Eazy \u2013 Lost in Translation}}</ref> The single topped the iTunes Electronic Songs Chart in Belgium and Finland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/2011/07/kyary-pamyu-pamyus-ponponpon-tops-itunes-charts-in-finland-belgium/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's \"PONPONPON\" tops iTunes charts in Finland + Belgium}}</ref> On August 3, 2011, her second promo single, \"Jelly\", was internationally released via [[iTunes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/jelly-single/id451007898 |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Jelly on iTunes |accessdate=March 7, 2015 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624113551/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/jelly-single/id451007898 |archivedate=June 24, 2013 }}</ref> A week after the release of ''Moshi Moshi Harajuku'', Pamyu Pamyu released an autobiography about her rise to fame titled, ''Oh! My God!! Harajuku Girl''.<ref>[http://tokyofashion.com/oh-my-god-harajuku-girl-by-kyary-pamyu-pamyu/ \"Oh! My! God! Harajuku Girl\" by Kyary Pamyu Pamyu]. Tokyofashion.com. Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref><ref>[https://www.amazon.co.jp/dp/4591125424 Oh! My God!! Harajuku Girl on Amazon Japan]. Amazon.com. Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref>\n[[File:\u30ed\u30f3\u30c9\u30f3\u30c1\u30e3\u30ec\u30f3\u30b8\u6c96\u7e04\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc (7034082301).jpg|left|thumb|Pamyu Pamyu performing at the [[4th Okinawa International Movie Festival]].]]\nOn December 6, 2011, her single \"[[Tsukematsukeru]]\" was digitally released internationally via iTunes. On December 9, Pamyu Pamyu made her American debut in [[Culver City, California]] to perform in a fashion show and play two of her songs, as well as her first time performing the single.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?kawaii_for_the_masses_rune_boutiques_debut_17854.aspx | title = Kawaii for the Masses: Rune Boutique's Debut | publisher = Asia Pacific Arts | date = January 25, 2012 | access-date = January 27, 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120609061813/http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?kawaii_for_the_masses_rune_boutiques_debut_17854.aspx | archive-date = June 9, 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref> \"Tsukematsukeru\" was released physically on January 11, 2012, which included a special edition photobook. It was eventually certified gold in April 2012. In February and March 2012, she represented Japan during Japanese performing arts exhibitions in Shanghai and Hong Kong. She performed on February 24 in Shanghai at the [[Shanghai Expo Mart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghaimart.com/news/news_article.asp?article_id=2958 |title=AKB48\u3001\u52a8\u6f2b\u6b4c\u624b\u3001DJ KAYA \u65e5\u672c\u8d85\u7ea7\u660e\u661f\u9635\u5bb9\u6fc0\u60c5\u7efd\u653e\"\u6d3b\u529b\u65e5\u672c\u5c55 |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403065133/http://www.shanghaimart.com/news/news_article.asp?article_id=2958 |archivedate=April 3, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghaimart.com/chinese/selfevent/20120224scr/events.html|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu \u7279\u522b\u6f14\u51fa&\u89c1\u9762\u4f1a|publisher=Shanghaimart|date=February 2012|language=zh|access-date=February 12, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403082603/http://www.shanghaimart.com/chinese/selfevent/20120224scr/events.html|archive-date=April 3, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hxgift.cn/Html/business/fair_guide/2012/2/15/145106.html |title=\u65e5\u672c\u5f53\u7ea2\u6f14\u827a\u52a8\u6f2b\u660e\u661f\u8054\u8882\u9996\u79c0\u4e0a\u6d77\uff0c\u4e9a\u6d32\u6d41\u884c\u5076\u50cf\u8d85\u8c6a\u534e\u6f14\u51fa\u9635\u5bb9\u9707\u64bc\u767b\u573a |accessdate=February 12, 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412163338/http://news.hxgift.cn/Html/business/fair_guide/2012/2/15/145106.html |archivedate=April 12, 2013 }}</ref> On March 27, Pamyu Pamyu performed for 700 fans in Hong Kong at the [[Kowloonbay International Trade & Exhibition Centre]]. She released her second single, \"[[Candy Candy (Kyary song)|Candy Candy]]\" as a digital download on March 14, 2012. The single debuted at eighty-nine on the Billboard Japan Hot 100, and later peaked at number two.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=hot100&year=2012&month=03&day=12|title=Billboard Japan Hot 100 {{!}} Charts {{!}} Billboard JAPAN|date=March 12, 2012|newspaper=Billboard JAPAN|language=ja-JP|access-date=November 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=hot100&year=2012&month=04&day=16|title=Billboard Japan Hot 100 {{!}} Charts {{!}} Billboard JAPAN|date=April 16, 2012|newspaper=Billboard JAPAN|language=ja-JP|access-date=November 14, 2016}}</ref> It was released as a CD single on April 4, 2012, and sold 9,913 copies its first week, debuting at number eight on the ''Oricon'' weekly singles chart.<ref>{{cite web|title=CD\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb \u9031\u9593\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0-ORICON STYLE \u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/rank/js/w/2012-04-16/more/2/|work=Oricon Style|publisher=Oricon Inc|accessdate=April 21, 2013}}</ref> Despite it being Pamyu Pamyu's first and only single to chart on the [[Recording Industry Association of Japan]] charts, \"Candy Candy\" remains Kyary's lowest-selling single to date at the time.\n\nHer debut full-length album, ''[[Pamyu Pamyu Revolution]]'', was released on May 23, 2012. Along with the announcement of her second single back in February, it was revealed that Pamyu Pamyu was planning to hold her first nationwide tour in June of that year, as well as launching an official fan club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://natalie.mu/music/news/65087|title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u30852nd\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30eb\uff06\u30c4\u30a2\u30fc\u767a\u8868\u3001FC\u3082\u8a2d\u7acb|publisher=natalie.mu| date = February 26, 2012}}</ref> The tour kicked off on June 2 at the Namba Hatch in Osaka. It continued in Hiroshima, Nagoya, Sendai, Sapporo, Fukuoka and finished in Tokyo on June 29. In July 2012, she made her European debut by performing for 13,000 fans at the Japan Expo in Paris.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/2012/07/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-holds-successful-live-in-paris-for-japan-expo/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu holds successful live in Paris for 'JAPAN EXPO'|publisher=Tokyo Hive| date = July 9, 2012}}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu was bestowed the title of \"Kawaii Harajuku Ambassador\" on August 30, 2012 by the Mayor of [[Shibuya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tokyofashion.com/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-harajuku-kawaii-ambassador/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Crowned Harajuku Kawaii Ambassador| date = September 5, 2012}}</ref> Following a montage of her successes performed on a large screen, she performed several songs in front of a crowd after accepting the award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mdpr.jp/021200511|title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3001\u539f\u5bbf\u30ab\u30ef\u30a4\u30a4\u5927\u4f7f\u306b\u5c31\u4efb\u300c\u5168\u4e16\u754c\u3092\u9ebb\u75fa\u3055\u305b\u305f\u3044\u300d| date = August 30, 2012}}</ref> In early September 2012, Pamyu Pamyu announced that she was collaborating with Japanese budget fashion brand [[g.u.]] for her new single \"[[Fashion Monster]]\", which was given a CD release date of October 17, 2012. She was also used as the image character for g.u. after the announcement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mdpr.jp/021201315|title=\u524d\u7530\u6566\u5b50\u306b\u7d9a\u304f\u300cg.u.\u300d\u30a4\u30e1\u30fc\u30b8\u30ad\u30e3\u30e9\u6c7a\u5b9a\u3000\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u300c\u79c1\u3067\u3044\u3044\u306e\u304b\u306a\u300d|date=September 5, 2012}}</ref> Around the same time, Pamyu Pamyu announced her debut world tour titled ''[[100%KPP World Tour|100% KPP World Tour]]'', which began in February 2013 and lasted until June. The tour visited the United States, United Kingdom, France, Belgium, Taiwan, Thailand, Singapore, Hong Kong, and her native Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2012/12/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-announces-the-schedule-for-her-1st-world-tour/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu announces the schedule for her 1st world tour|date=December 22, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyary.asobisystem.com/world2013/en/|title=100%KPP WORLD TOUR|date=January 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013\u20132014: ''Nanda Collection'' and ''Pika Pika Fantajin'' ===\n\nDuring 2012 and 2013, she began receiving more attention in Western media. [[Sputnikmusic]] listed ''[[Pamyu Pamyu Revolution]]'' as number one on their \"Best Pop Albums of 2012\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sputnikmusic.com/best/albums/2012/pop|title=Best Pop Albums of 2012| year = 2012}}</ref> Britain's ''[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused magazine]]'' became an enthusiastic supporter. Pamyu Pamyu was photographed by Matt Irwin for the magazine's December 2012 issue, styled by [[Nicola Formichetti]].<ref name=\"KYARY PAMYU PAMYU COVERSHOOT\" /> The magazine also cited her video for \"[[Furisodation]]\" in their \"Video of the Week\" category in January 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/15404/1/the-agony-the-ecstasy|title=This week's Kyary Pamyu Pamyu vids, XXYYXX mash-ups and a Grimes remix from Four Tet| date = January 15, 2013}}</ref> and named her \"The Star of Tomorrow\" in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/artsandculture/article/16878/1/top-ten-reasons-to-become-a-pamyu-pamyu-fan|title=2013 TO INFINITY: WHY PAMYU PAMYU IS THE STAR OF TOMORROW| date = August 23, 2013}}</ref> In January 2013, [[MTV|MTV Iggy]] called Pamyu Pamyu \"the coolest girl on the planet\" and ''[[The Fader]]'' called her \"the most exciting person making music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2013/01/09/video-kyary-pamyu-pamyu-furisodation/|title=Video: Kyary Pamyu Pamyu, \"Furisodation\"| date = January 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtviggy.com/blog-posts/kyary-pamyu-pamyus-%E2%80%9Cfurisodeshon%E2%80%9D-pv-is-red-hot/ |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's \"Furisodeshon\" PV Is Red Hot |date=January 9, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403142917/http://www.mtviggy.com/blog-posts/kyary-pamyu-pamyus-%E2%80%9Cfurisodeshon%E2%80%9D-pv-is-red-hot/ |archivedate=April 3, 2013 }}</ref> Furisodeshon's video was also named by [[Stereogum]] as a \"Video of the Week\" in January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stereogum.com/1234072/the-5-best-videos-of-the-week-64/franchises/straight-to-video/|title=The 5 Best Videos of the Week| date = January 11, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Elle (magazine)|Elle France]]'' promoted Pamyu Pamyu in its February 2013 issue,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://agath3kitty.tumblr.com/post/42577826690/elle-magazine-kyary-pamyu-kpp-kawai-hair |title=Elle France |date=February 10, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EJyyHS3e?url=http://agath3kitty.tumblr.com/post/42577826690/elle-magazine-kyary-pamyu-kpp-kawai-hair |archivedate=February 10, 2013 }}</ref> and she appeared on the French television show ''[[Le Petit Journal (Canal+)|Le Petit Journal]]'' on February 11.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-de-stars.com/le-petit-journal/le-petit-journal-recoit-le-phenomene-japonais-kyary-pamyu-pamyu_art75219.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214040403/http://www.news-de-stars.com/le-petit-journal/le-petit-journal-recoit-le-phenomene-japonais-kyary-pamyu-pamyu_art75219.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 14, 2013|title=Le Petit Journal re\u00e7oit le ph\u00e9nom\u00e8ne japonais Kyary Pamyu Pamyu|date=February 11, 2013}}</ref> During this period, she also appeared in the Swedish newspaper ''[[Svenska Dagbladet]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://maririma.tumblr.com/post/37918614220/kyarypamyupamyu-in-swedish-newspaper |title=Swedish newspaper article |date=February 10, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EJyzKrar?url=http://maririma.tumblr.com/post/37918614220/kyarypamyupamyu-in-swedish-newspaper |archivedate=February 10, 2013 }}</ref> and was interviewed on the British radio station [[Monocle (lifestyle magazine)#Radio|Monocle 24]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://monocle.com/radio/shows/culture/71/|title=Monocle 24: Culture, episode 71|date=February 18, 2013|access-date=February 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014040557/http://monocle.com/radio/shows/culture/71/|archive-date=October 14, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> February also saw the release of Pamyu Pamyu's first concert DVD/Blu-ray, ''[[Dokidoki Wakuwaku Pamyu Pamyu Revolution Land]]'', recorded live in November 2012 at the [[Nippon Budokan]] in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/2012/12/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-to-release-her-budokan-live-on-dvd-blu-ray/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu to release her Budokan live on DVD & Blu-ray| date = December 28, 2012}}</ref> A month-long exhibition in March 2013 titled \"Kyary Pamyu Pamuseum\" was held in Tokyo's [[Roppongi Hills]] complex, showcasing all costumes from her music videos and live performances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyary.asobisystem.com/topics/index.php?id=50|title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085\u8863\u88c5\u5c55\u958b\u50ac\u6c7a\u5b9a\uff01| date = February 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyarymuseum.jp/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamuseum| date = February 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tokyogirlsupdate.com/2013/02/kyary-pamyu-pamuseum-costume-exhibition.html |title=KyaryPamyuPamyu to hold her first costume exhibition in March!\uff01 |date=March 27, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313212146/http://tokyogirlsupdate.com/2013/02/kyary-pamyu-pamuseum-costume-exhibition.html |archivedate=March 13, 2013 }}</ref> In April, a deal for American distribution was reached with Sire Records, and \"[[Fashion Monster]]\" was re-released in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skopemag.com/2013/04/09/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-performing-in-new-york-and-los-angeles|title=KYARY PAMYU PAMYU PERFORMING IN NEW YORK AND LOS ANGELES| date = April 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Fashion-Monster/dp/B00CJSHDI8/ref=sr_1_2?s=music&ie=UTF8&qid=1367078256&sr=1-2&keywords=kyary+pamyu+pamyu+fashion+monster |title=Fashion Monster |date=April 27, 2013 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In summer 2013, Pamyu Pamyu's television series ''TV John!'' was broadcast in France on the [[Nolife (TV channel)|Nolife]] channel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tokyogirlsupdate.com/2013/06/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-to-tvjohn-france.html |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's show goes global! |date=June 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130818092302/http://tokyogirlsupdate.com/2013/06/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-to-tvjohn-france.html |archivedate=August 18, 2013 }}</ref> In America, ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' featured her in its July issue,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.papermag.com/2013/07/girl_talk_charli_xcx_tecla_kyary_pamyu_pamyu_ame.php|title=WE CHAT WITH FOUR ON-THE-RISE POP SINGERS ABOUT THEIR CRAZY STYLE| date = July 15, 2013}}</ref> and she received her largest American exposure to date in a lengthy profile in ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' the same month.<ref name=\"biointerview\" />\n\n[[File:Kyary Pamyu Pamyu at MTV VMAJ 2014 (1).jpg|thumb|Pamyu Pamyu at the 2014 [[MTV Video Music Awards Japan]] red carpet.]]Pamyu Pamyu performed her songs \"[[Invader Invader]]\" and \"[[Ninja Re Bang Bang]]\" at the end ceremony for the [[2013 MTV Video Music Awards Japan]] Awards, where she also received the awards for Best Pop Video and Best Karaoke! Song for \"[[Fashion Monster]]\". In late June, it was revealed that she is working on a documentary film that is due out late 2013 entitled ''Kyary Pamyu Pamyu the Movie''. The film featured one-day limited screening and concert footage from Pamyu Pamyu's 100% KPP World Tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tokyogirlsupdate.com/2013/06/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-movie.html |accessdate=August 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809075036/http://tokyogirlsupdate.com/2013/06/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-movie.html |archivedate=August 9, 2013 |title=Check Out the Trailers for Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's Documentary Movie! |publisher=Tokyo Girls' Update }}</ref> Internationally the same year, she was nominated for Best New International Pop Artist by [[Fuse TV]] and Best Japan Act at the [[2013 MTV Europe Music Awards]].<ref name=\"MTV Europe Music Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://tv.mtvema.com/news/2013-nominations/t1r05w|title=MTV Europe Music Awards| date = September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Fuse TV Best New Artist Poll\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2013/08/best-new-artist-fan-poll#6|title=Fuse TV Best New Artist Poll| date = August 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"allkpop.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allkpop.com/article/2013/08/g-dragon-and-cl-nominated-for-best-new-artist-by-fuse-tv|title=G-Dragon and CL nominated for Best New Artist by Fuse TV| date = August 30, 2013}}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu's second studio album, ''[[Nanda Collection]]'', was released on June 26, 2013.<ref name=\"Nanda\">{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2013/05/24/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-reveals-new-pics-and-info-on-2nd-album |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Reveals New Pics and Info on 2nd Album |publisher=Crunchyroll |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> In September 2013, she announced a second world tour titled ''[[Nanda Collection World Tour]]'' and a new single \"[[Mottai Night Land]]\" was released in late October and received positive reviews from Western media outlets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2013/09/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-to-embark-on-her-2nd-world-tour-next-year|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu to release new single + embark on her 2nd world tour next year| date = September 7, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2013/10/23/video-kyary-pamyu-pamyu-mottai-night-land/ |title=Video: Kyary Pamyu Pamyu, \"Mottai Night Land\" |publisher=The Fader |date=October 23, 2013 |accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2013/10/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-mottai-night-land-video/ |title=Watch Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's Dream-Like 'Mottai Night Land' Video |work=Spin|date=October 24, 2013 |accessdate=November 6, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oystermag.com/watch-j-pop-princess-kyary-pamyu-pamyus-new-video |title=Watch: J-Pop Princess Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's New Video |publisher=Oystermag.com |date=October 23, 2013 |accessdate=October 23, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027041346/http://oystermag.com/watch-j-pop-princess-kyary-pamyu-pamyus-new-video |archive-date=October 27, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The single was released on November 6.<ref>[http://nihongogo.com/2013/10/kyary-pamyu-pmayu-to-release-new-single-in-november/ Kyary Pamyu Pamyu To Release New Single In November] Z. Konno, Nihongogo</ref> The world tour visited the United States, Canada, Australia, England, France, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, Singapore, Hong Kong, and Pamyu Pamyu's native Japan, lasting from February until November. It was originally to last until June but was postponed due to [[2014 Thai coup d'\u00e9tat|political unrest]]. She was interviewed by or was the focus of articles in internationally renowned publications such as ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out London]]'', ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'', and ''[[Vice (magazine)|VICE]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/australia-culture-blog/2014/mar/21/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-tinges-j-pop-horror-show|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu tinges J-pop's cuteness with a touch of horror show|newspaper=The Guardian |date=March 21, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/dream-believer-20140306-3480u.html|title=Dream Believer|work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=March 8, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-is-the-david-lynch-of-j-pop|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Is the David Lynch of J-Pop|magazine=VICE magazine |date=March 13, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/music/whats-the-deal-with-kyary-pamyu-pamyu|title=What's the deal with\u2026 Kyary Pamyu Pamyu? |magazine=Time Out London |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> in April 2014, Pamyu Pamyu made her Australian television debut on the program ''[[Sunrise (Australian TV program)|Sunrise]]'' and was the focus of Australian news programs such as ''[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.tv.yahoo.com/sunrise/video/watch/22226470/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-performs-live/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu performs LIVE |magazine=Time Out London |date=April 6, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-03-24/japanese-pop-star-kyary-pamyu-pamyu-plays-her/5342368|title=Japanese pop star Kyary Pamyu Pamyu plays her debut show in Sydney |publisher=ABC News |date=March 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://asbs.jp/english/interview.php?id=505|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Performs Robot Dance for First Time at Sydney Show! Next Nationwide Hall Tour Announced! |publisher=ASBS |date=March 24, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> In May 2014, she appeared in the British fashion magazine ''[[i-D]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://i-d.vice.com/en_gb/read/interviews/2699/kyary-pamyu-pamyu |title=sweeter than candy, better than cake, kyary pamyu pamyu is the no. 1 j-pop star! |publisher=i-D Magazine |date=May 27, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529150717/http://i-d.vice.com/en_gb/read/interviews/2699/kyary-pamyu-pamyu |archive-date=May 29, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In July 2014, ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' premiered Pamyu Pamyu's first English-language song, \"Ring A Bell,\" in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/946909/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-ring-a-bell-premiere-all-english-single/|title=The World Premiere of Japanese Pop Star Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's First All-English Single|magazine=Vogue |date=July 14, 2014 |accessdate=January 3, 2015}}</ref> In October 2014, she was the focus of an article and photoshoot in the American fashion magazine ''[[Nylon (magazine)|Nylon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nylon.com/articles/kyary-pamyu-pamyu|title=kyary pamyu pamyu is taking over the internet |magazine=Nylon Magazine |date=October 13, 2014 |accessdate=December 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, Pamyu Pamyu announced her single \"[[Yume no Hajima Ring Ring]]\" in which her theme would be \"evolution\" which provides a theme relating to graduation. The music video was uploaded to YouTube on February 19. The single was released on February 26. In March, she announced that her upcoming single \"[[Family Party (song)|Family Party]]\" will be used as an ending theme for the movie ''[[Crayon Shin-chan: Serious Battle! Robot Dad Strikes Back]]''. Pamyu Pamyu has stated that this is her first original theme song for a film.<ref>{{cite web | date=March 5, 2014 | url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2014/03/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-to-provide-theme-song-for-new-crayon-shin-chan-movie | title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu to provide theme song for new 'Crayon Shin-chan' movie| publisher=Tokyohive | accessdate=March 5, 2014}}</ref> \"Family Party\" was released on April 16. On May 9, she announced her first limited-run single, \"[[Kira Kira Killer]]\", which was released on June 11. The single was featured in commercials for au's \"Lucky\" campaign. Also in May, ''[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused]]'' announced that Pamyu Pamyu was working with international musicians [[Sophie (musician)|Sophie]] and [[Yelle]] on new upcoming music.<ref>{{cite web | date=May 15, 2014 | url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/19825/1/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-gets-kawaii-with-sophie | title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu gets kawaii with Sophie| publisher=Dazed & Confused | accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> she announced at her Zepp Tokyo concert that she would be releasing her third full album, titled ''[[Pika Pika Fantajin]]'' on July 9, 2014. Along with the album announcement on May 18, Pamyu Pamyu also announced that she would be holding an arena tour after her hall tour in Japan. Both nationwide tours were held after the Nanda Collection World Tour. The Hall tour consisted of 17 shows in 13 cities, visiting Saitama, Tokyo, Miyagi, Matsudo, Hokkaido, Tochigi, Niigata, Ishikawa, Yamanashi, Chiba, Hiroshima, Kagawa, and Aichi, and lasting from July 27 until September 22. The arena tour consisted of nine shows in five cities, which ran from October 18 to November 9, visiting the cities of Makuhari, Osaka, Nagoya, Fukuoka, and Yoyogi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asbs.jp/english/news.php?id=1081|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Announces New Album & Arena Tour|publisher=Kyary Asobi system|accessdate=May 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://asbs.jp/english/news.php?id=1104|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Reveals Tracklist and Cover Art for 'Pika Pika Fantasian'|publisher=Kyary Asobi System|accessdate=May 31, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531183135/http://asbs.jp/english/news.php?id=1104|archive-date=May 31, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132016: ''KPP Best''===\n[[File:\u897f\u6b669101F.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The Seibu KPP Train in 2016. [[Seibu 9000 series]]]]\nIn January 2015, she was mentioned by ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' as one of the \"major recent sellers\" for [[Warner Music Group]] alongside artists including [[Coldplay]] and [[Ed Sheeran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/warner-music-loses-24-million-756658|title=Warner Music Loses $24 Million in Most Recent Quarter | work=The Hollywood Reporter | first=Paul|last=Bond|date=December 11, 2014}}</ref> In March 2015, Pamyu Pamyu released her single \"[[Mondai Girl]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url = http://aramajapan.com/news/music/musicvideo/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-shows-her-visual-versatility-with-mondai-girl/16961/|title = Kyary Pamyu Pamyu shows her visual versatility with 'Mondai Girl'|work = Arama Japan|date = February 2015}}</ref> In June, she was chosen by the international cosmetic brand [[MAC Cosmetics]] as one of its \"Global Heroes\" and was profiled in an interview on their website.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.maccosmetics.com/culture/global-heroes/kyary-pamyu-pamyu|title=KYARY PAMYU PAMYU | work=MAC Cosmetics | first=Colleen|last=Nika|date=June 24, 2015}}</ref> In the following month, Pamyu Pamyu was chosen to represent Japan in Italy at [[Expo 2015]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2015/05/03/music/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-brings-kawaii-italian-debut/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu brings 'kawaii' in Italian debut | work=Japan Times | first=Patrick|last=St. Michel|date=May 3, 2015}}</ref> On June 17, 2015, a remake of the movie ''[[Nutcracker Fantasy]]'' with a remix of her song \"[[Pamyu Pamyu Revolution|Oyasumi]]\" as the theme song. On September 2, 2015, Pamyu Pamyu released the Halloween-themed single \"[[Crazy Party Night (Pumpkin no Gyakush\u016b)]]\" and began the Crazy Party Night 2015 Tour, a nationwide concert tour that lasted until December 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://tokyogirlsupdate.com/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-11th-info-20150750351.html|title = Crazy Party Nights Coming Soon! Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's 11th Single! 1st MV Collection! 3rd UK Live! Autumn Tour!|work = Tokyo Girls Update|first = (editor)|date = July 3, 2015|last = Okkun}}</ref> The music video for the single premiered beforehand on August 20, 2016 and has since amassed over thirteen million views as of May 2018. On October 11, 2015, she played a one-off international concert at [[The Roundhouse]] in London, England.<ref>{{cite news|url = http://www.londoncitynights.com/2015/10/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-at-roundhouse-11th.html|title = 'Kyary Pamyu Pamyu' at the Roundhouse, 11th October 2015|work = London City Nights|date = October 12, 2015|first = David C.|last = James}}</ref> In November 2015, Pamyu Pamyu was featured prominently in advertising for \"The World Goes Pop\" exhibition at the [[Tate Modern]] national art gallery in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/art/the-world-goes-pop-at-tate-modern-your-ultimate-guide|title='The World Goes Pop' at Tate Modern: your ultimate guide | work=Time Out London | first=Phoebe|last=Trimingham|date=November 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huma3.com/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-presents-the-exhibition-the-world-goes-pop/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu presents the exhibition The World Goes Pop! | work=Huma3 |date=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn May 25, 2016, her debut compilation album ''[[KPP Best]]'' was released, featuring her single \"[[Sai & Co]]\" which was released on April 20. Around that time, Pamyu Pamyu announced a third world tour titled the Five Years Monster World Tour. The world tour visited Singapore, London, Sydney, Melbourne, San Francisco, New York City, Taipei, and Tokyo.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}} Her first art exhibition titled the Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Artwork Exhibition 2011\u20132016 was held at [[Laforet|Laforet Harajuku]] from December 16. In addition to every CD jacket design being present at the event, there will be well over 100 images on display including unseen photos from Pamyu Pamyu's photobooks that are available exclusively within her album releases, outfits and wigs worn by Pamyu Pamyu herself, interactive displays of the jacket images, and much, much more. This is the ultimate Kyary Pamyu Pamyu artwork exhibition collecting together 5 years of work since her debut. In conjunction with the exhibition was released the book \"Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Art Works 2011\u20132016\", compiling around 300 unseen images from her photobooks. It is Pamyu Pamyu's first release together with art director and designer Steve Nakamura, who has been responsible for the art direction of Kyary's releases since her debut in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/20731|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's First art exhibition to be held at Laforet Harajuku from December 16th! | work=MoshiMoshiNippon|date=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017\u201318: ''Japamyu'' ===\nOn December 27, 2016, she announced that she would be collaborating with English singer [[Charli XCX]] on Yasutaka Nakata's solo track \"[[Crazy Crazy/Harajuku Iyahoi|Crazy Crazy]]\". The song was released on January 18, 2017, followed later in January by her single \"[[Crazy Crazy/Harajuku Iyahoi|Harajuku Iyahoi]]\". In April 2017, Pamyu Pamyu released the single \"[[Easta]]\". From August 12, 2017 to October 1, 2017, the new exhibition titled the Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Art Exhibition 2011\u20132016 in Taipei was released, the event will feature displays of all 18 CD sleeves since her debut back in 2011, as well as outfits and wigs worn by Pamyu Pamyu herself in music videos, unreleased works from photo books that come with her albums and more.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/52066|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Artwork Exhibition to Open in Taiwan's Capital City Taipei!|work=MoshiMoshiNippon|access-date=July 19, 2017}}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu also embarked on a tour titled The Spooky Obakeyashiki: Pumpkins Strike Back in 2017. The following year, she performed at 6 international concerts in London, Cologne, Berlin, New York, San Francisco, and Los Angeles as The Spooky Obakeyashiki World Tour.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8377035/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-new-single-world-tour-katy-perry-interview|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Talks New Single, World Tour, Meeting Katy Perry: Interview|work=Billboard|access-date=May 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard\" /> In an interview with ''Billboard'' Japan, Pamyu Pamyu stated that although her music and performance style have evolved, she hopes to \"maintain that basic 'kawaii' side\" her music and style is known for.<ref name=\"Billboard\" /> Over a year since the release of \"Easta\", she released the single \"[[Kimino Mikata]]\" on April 11, 2018, along with an accompanying music video.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tokyohive.com/article/2018/04/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-releases-pv-for-kimi-no-mikata|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu releases PV for 'Kimino Mikata' {{!}} tokyohive.com|website=www.tokyohive.com|access-date=May 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Pamyu Pamyu released her fourth studio album ''[[Japamyu]]'', her first studio album in four years. The album included her 2016 single \"Sai & Kou\" as well as \"Harajuku Iyahoi\" and \"Kimino Mikata\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/122512|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Announces 4th Album \u2018Japamyu\u2019 to be Released on September 26|work=Moshi Moshi Nippon|access-date=August 18, 2018}}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu performed a new song from the album titled \"Kizunami\" on [[Music Station]] on September 7. On that same year, her contract with WMG expired.\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: Concert tours and \"Kimi ga Iine Kuretara\" ===\nOn March 20, 2019, Pamyu Pamyu announced a new concert tour, \"Oto no Kuni Live Tour\", which commenced on March 30 at Izumo-taisha Shrine in [[Shimane Prefecture|Shimane]].<ref>https://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/187114 Kyary Pamyu Pamyu to Perform Kabuki Themed Concert at Japan\u2019s Oldest Kabuki Theatre</ref> On May 10, she released an independent digital single \"[[Kimi ga Iine Kuretara]]\" as a tie-up song to the Japanese drama ''Mukai no Bazuru Kazoku''. In January 2020, Pamyu Pamyu was announced as a performer at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] 2020 in Indio, California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://j-generation.com/kyary-pamyu-and-pamyu-and-hatsune-miku-to-turn-coachella-kawaii-in-2020/|title=Kyary Pamyu and Pamyu and Hatsune Miku to turn Coachella \"kawaii\" in 2020|date=January 3, 2020|website=J-Generation|access-date=January 3, 2020}}</ref> Due to [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] ''Kamaitachi TOUR'' has been cancelled and overseas shows have also been postponed. Unable to perform live for everyone during the current situation, Kyary is releasing a curated selection of her past live concerts on YouTube starting from April 14, 2020, available for a limited time until May 17, 2020. <ref>https://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/313974 Stay Home With Kyary Pamyu Pamyu as She Releases Past Live Concerts On YouTube</ref>\n\n==Artistry==\n\n===Public image===\n[[File:Kyary Pamyu Pamyu (9388083915).jpg|thumb|Pamyu Pamyu performing at J-Pop Summit in San Francisco, July 2013]]\nAs a musical entertainer, Pamyu Pamyu has been recognized as the \"J-Pop Princess\" or \"Harajuku Pop Princess\".<ref>[http://www.mtvhive.com/2013/04/16/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-new-york-photos/#/0 J-Pop Star Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Debuts in New York City \u2013 Photos]. [[MTV]].</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://popdust.com/2013/05/12/j-pop-princess-kyary-pamyu-pamyu-finally-does-dubstep/ |title=Wacky J-pop Princess, Kyary Pamyu Pamyu, Goes Dubstep |publisher=Popdust |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nHer fashion sense is the subject of much media coverage. Pamyu Pamyu is often called \"Japan's [[Lady Gaga]]\",<ref name=\"ladygaga\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bilerico.com/2011/07/is_this_japans_lady_gaga.php |title=Is Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Japan's Lady Gaga? &#124; The Bilerico Project |publisher=Bilerico.com |date=July 29, 2011 |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> citing her similar use of fashion to attract attention.<ref name=\"kanja\">{{cite web|url=http://www.asianjunkie.com/2012/06/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-apologizes-to-kanjani8-fans-netizens-tell-her-fuck-them/ |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu apologizes to Kanjani8 fans, netizens tell her \"fuck them\" |publisher=Asian Junkie |date=June 18, 2012 |accessdate=July 20, 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150215090346/http://www.asianjunkie.com/2012/06/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-apologizes-to-kanjani8-fans-netizens-tell-her-fuck-them |archivedate=February 15, 2015}}</ref> According to a review of her London concert, a press release stated \"[Kyary] is not supposed to be musically talented. She is more about image featuring her creative fashion sense as one of the main subjects of her career, not just the music.\"<ref name=\"LondonSenpai\">{{cite web|url=http://londonsenpai.wordpress.com/2013/02/17/kyary-pamyu-pamyus-world-tour-concert-in-london-review/ |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu's World Tour Concert in London Review &#124; londonsenpai |publisher=Londonsenpai.wordpress.com |date=February 17, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> She has cited American singers [[Gwen Stefani]], [[Katy Perry]], and [[Lady Gaga]] as her inspirations in both music and fashion.<ref name=\"Interview\" /> Pamyu Pamyu's fashion sense has also been criticized. While being interviewed on TV Asahi's ''Music Station'', she was wearing an oversized ribbon on her head, which blocked Japanese boy band [[Kanjani8]] from being seen on camera, angering fans of Kanjani8 by her outrageous fashion style. She later stated that when she is being interviewed on television, she will restrict what she is wearing.<ref name=\"kanja\" /> Pamyu Pamyu's fans, however, defended her wearing the outfit.<ref name=\"kanja\" /> Pamyu Pamyu cites \"kawaii\" (meaning \"cute\" or \"cuteness\") as her background style.<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|last=Bryan |first=Beverly |url=http://www.mtviggy.com/interviews/cray-pop-the-kawaii-genius-of-kyary-pamyu-pamyu/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140802130804/http://www.mtviggy.com/interviews/cray-pop-the-kawaii-genius-of-kyary-pamyu-pamyu/ |archive-date=August 2, 2014 |url-status=dead |title=Cray Pop: The Kawaii Genius of Kyary Pamyu Pamyu |publisher=Mtv Iggy |date=July 16, 2012 |accessdate=November 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHer international success has also received much attention. During an interview with ''[[The Fader]]'', Pamyu Pamyu was asked if she meant to make music outside of Asia, where she responded; \"At first, I didn't think about global markets at all. But even in Japanese, my lyrics don't make any sense and have a kind of mystery, like on \"[[Pon Pon Pon]]\" and \"[[Tsukematsukeru]]\". I can feel that what I'm doing in Japanese is catchy to global audiences anyway.\"<ref name=\"Interview\" /> [[Keiichi Ishizaka]], chairman and chief executive officer of Warner Music Japan Inc, commenting on her image to ''[[The Japan Times]]'', says \"[Kyary] is a person who came directly out of Tokyo's Harajuku culture, and there is a growing international interest in Japan's ''kawaii'' culture,\"<ref name=\"japantimes\" /> Many critics and publications noted the increase of popularity within the Japanese popular culture outside Japan, such as its fashion and animation, and she is serving as its global ambassador. Ishizaka believed that with the advent of the Internet, there is no difference in time and distance among countries anymore.\"<ref name=\"japantimes\">{{cite web|url=http://the-japan-news.com/news/article/0000708084 |title=The Japan News |publisher=The Japan News |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref>[[Seibu Railway]] honored her by running a train on the [[Seibu Ikebukuro Line]], part of their [[Seibu 9000 series]], from June to September 2016, themed on their pop star's music videos, with carriages idolized with her images, which also passed through her birthplace [[Nishit\u014dky\u014d, Tokyo]].<ref>[https://www.nippon.com/en/views/b05104/ All Aboard the Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Train!]</ref>\n\n===Musical style and videos===\nSince her debut in 2011, her music has been exclusively produced by musician Yasutaka Nakata of electronic music duo Capsule, which also produces music for girl group [[Perfume (Japanese band)|Perfume]] and once for singers like [[Meg (singer)|Meg]], [[Ami Suzuki]], and [[SMAP]]. Despite this collaboration with technopop artists and charting on electronic music charts, most media outlets do not classify Pamyu Pamyu under the genre due to Nakata's musical style for her, which is different from his other produced acts.\n\n{{cquote|''I love grotesque things. My concept is scary things that become traumatic with their cuteness. There are so many 'just cute' things in the world, so I add grotesque, scary and even shocking materials like eyeballs and brains to balance out the cuteness.'' <small>Kyary Pamyu Pamyu; interview with ''The Fader''<ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2013/04/16/interview-kyary-pamyu-pamyu/ |title=Interview: Kyary Pamyu Pamyu |publisher=The Fader |date=16 April 2013 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref></small>}}\n\n===In the media===\nAs of August 2016, she has gained over 4.4&nbsp;million followers on the social media site Twitter, making her the most followed female celebrity in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://meyou.jp/ranking/|title=Twitter\u65e5\u672c \u30d5\u30a9\u30ed\u30ef\u30fc\u6570 \u7dcf\u5408\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0 1\u201350\u4f4d Twitter\u3067\u5199\u771f\u516c\u958b|date=August 5, 2013|work=meyou.jp|accessdate=September 27, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu's debut single \"Pon Pon Pon\" is one of the most viewed music videos in Japan, garnering over 100,000,000 views as of September 2016.<ref name=\"MTV\">[http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2011/08/04/mtv-pop-music-show-bigger-than-the-buzz-summer-artists-cats-grilling/ Favorite Summer Artists & Cats Grilling Out (!!!): It's Episode 2 Of MTV's Pop Music Web Show, 'Bigger Than The Buzz'!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617131231/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2011/08/04/mtv-pop-music-show-bigger-than-the-buzz-summer-artists-cats-grilling/ |date=June 17, 2012 }}. MTV.com (August 4, 2011). Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref><ref name=\"Dooling\"/><ref name=\"biointerview\">{{cite news| url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2013/07/27/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-takes-pop-beyond-cute/ | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Takes Pop Beyond Cute \u2013 Speakeasy \u2013 WSJ | accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Warner Music Japan|title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085 \u2013 PONPONPON, Kyary Pamyu Pamyu \u2013 PONPONPON|date=July 16, 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yzC4hFK5P3g|accessdate=October 22, 2016}}</ref> The music video, which has been influenced by '60s and '70s fashion along with the main Japanese theme kawaii, has received huge media attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://white-screen.jp/?p=9761 |title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3001\u539f\u5bbf\u304b\u3089\u4e16\u754c\u3092\u5e2d\u5dfb!? \u7530\u5411\u6f64\u76e3\u7763\u304c\u660e\u304b\u3059MV\u300cPONPONPON\u300d\u304c\u51fa\u6765\u308b\u307e\u3067!! |publisher=white-screen.jp |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> American recording artist [[Katy Perry]] had tweeted about the music, indicating that she is a fan of hers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/katyperry/status/161022559545073664 |title=Twitter / katyperry: I'm so in love with her but |publisher=Twitter |date=January 22, 2012 |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}{{Primary source inline|date=February 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany of Pamyu Pamyu's singles, including \"[[Candy Candy]]\", \"[[Invader Invader]]\", and \"[[Fashion Monster]]\" have generated millions of views on the social streaming site YouTube. Her single \"[[Furisodation]]\", however, generated minor controversy in her native Japan, where a citizens' group believed the video encouraged alcohol and smoking, in which her label declined.<ref>[http://www.asahi.com/culture/update/0130/TKY201301300533.html \u671d\u65e5\u65b0\u805e\u30c7\u30b8\u30bf\u30eb\uff1a\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3071\u307f\u3085\u3055\u3093\u3001\u65b0\u66f2\uff30\uff36\u3067\u4e00\u6c17\u98f2\u307f\uff1f \u2013 \u30ab\u30eb\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002192536/http://www.asahi.com/culture/update/0130/TKY201301300533.html |date=October 2, 2013 }}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu's breakthrough single \"Pon Pon Pon\" was featured in the American cartoon ''[[The Simpsons]]'' in the 2014 episode \"[[Married to the Blob]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2014/05/15/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-simpsons|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu on The Simpsons! |publisher=SBS Pop Asia |date=May 15, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref> The single also appears in ''[[Just Dance Wii 2]];'' \"[[Ninja Re Bang Bang]]\" and \"Tsukematsukeru\" appear in ''[[Just Dance Wii U]]'', Japanese games, unless emulators are used (or Homebrew), they have yet to be playable outside Japan. The former and \"Koi Koi Koi\" are briefly featured in the 2016 animated film ''[[Sing (2016 American film)|Sing]]'', sung by an aspiring girl group composed of five Japanese-speaking red pandas. Pamyu Pamyu herself appeared at the film's premiere in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/22947 |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu walked the red carpet at the world premiere of the upcoming animated film \"SING\" from the \"Minions\" staff! |publisher=Moshi Moshi Nippon |date=December 5, 2016}}</ref> Several of her songs are also found prominently in several releases of the [[Namco]] rhythm game series ''[[Taiko no Tatsujin]]''.\n\nThe character Sylvie Paula Paula in the 2016 video game ''[[The King of Fighters XIV]]'' is modeled after Pamyu Pamyu.\n\n==Personal life==\nAlthough Pamyu Pamyu knows some English, she is not completely fluent and often has an [[Language interpretation|interpreter]] while overseas, and prefers to speak in Japanese for interviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whysojapan.com/tag/kyary-pamyu-pamyu/ |title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu &#124; WhysSoJapan? |publisher=Whysojapan.com |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> As of 2014, she has been studying English and spoke to the audience in brief bits of English during her concerts in London, United States and Australia, and on the [[NHK World]] show ''Moshimoshi Nippon''. When asked in an interview in 2016 about Pamyu Pamyu's progress of studying English, she stated, \"Not very good, not at all\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Music Feeds|title=Interview: Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Talks Australian Tour 2016|date=June 23, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RGoSr6lIKfc|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe dated [[Sekai no Owari]] lead vocalist Satoshi Fukase from June 2013 until August 15, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://narinari.com/Nd/20130621895.html |title=\u304d\u3083\u308a\u30fc\u3068\u30bb\u30ab\u30aa\u30ef\u6df1\u702c\u4ea4\u969b\u304b\u3001Twitter\u76ee\u6483\u8ac7\u3084\u5973\u6027\u8a8c\u304c\u30c7\u30fc\u30c8\u5831\u9053\u3002 |publisher=Narinari.com |date=June 11, 2013 |accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://majide2ch.blogspot.fr/2013/09/kyary-pamyu-pamyu-and-satoshi-fukase.html|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu and Satoshi Fukase (Sekai no Owari) spotted by Friday|publisher=MAJI DE?!|date=September 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpopasia.com/news/sekai-no-owaris-fukase-and-kyary-pamyu-pamyu-mutually-agreed-to-break-up::18905.html|title=SEKAI NO OWARI's Fukase & Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Mutually Agreed To Break Up|publisher=JPOPASIA|date=January 11, 2016}}</ref> Pamyu Pamyu is friends with members of [[Perfume (Japanese band)|Perfume]], as they both share times during recording with their producer Yasutaka Nakata. In a July 2014 live interview with Space Shower TV, she stated that she frequently communicates with the members either through Line or e-mail. On the other hand, the members of Perfume have explicitly stated that they also listen to Pamyu Pamyu's songs, specifically member [[Ayaka Nishiwaki|A-Chan]], who admitted that some of her songs sound identical to theirs but still enjoys listening as by crediting Nakata working with other artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/culture/2012/05/18/music/will-the-world-soon-wake-up-to-the-scent-of-perfume/|title=Will the world soon wake up to the scent of Perfume?|work=Japan Times}}</ref>\n\nShe is an anime and manga fan and has mentioned that her favorite anime show and manga is ''[[Crayon Shin-Chan]]''. Pamyu Pamyu has also mentioned that she is a [[Vocaloid]] fan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kyarychan.tumblr.com/aboutkyary |title=kyarychan |publisher=Kyarychan.tumblr.com |accessdate=July 20, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140712051846/http://kyarychan.tumblr.com/aboutkyary |archive-date=July 12, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Kyary Pamyu Pamyu the Movie''\n| Herself\n| Movie<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kyary.asobisystem.com/world2013/|title=100%KPP WORLD TOUR 2013}}</ref>\n| Documentary\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Kyary Pamyu Pamyu Cinema John!''\n| Herself\n| Movie<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinemajohn.com/|title=cinemajohn.com|access-date=June 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617192839/http://cinemajohn.com/|archive-date=June 17, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Crayon Shin-chan: Crash! Rakuga Kingdom and Almost Four Heroes|Crayon Shin-chan: Clash! Graffitingdom and Nearly Four Heroes]]''\n| Princess \n| Movie<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shinchan-movie.com/ambassador/|title=Shin-chan Movie Ambassador|access-date=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| Voice\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Network\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Kyary Pamyu Pamyu TV John!''\n| Herself / Host\n| [[Nagoya TV]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nagoyatv.com/kpp_john/|title=Kyary Pamyu Pamyu TV John!}}</ref>\n| Japanese variety show\n|-\n| 2011\u20132013\n| ''Space Shower Area''\n| Herself / VJ\n| [[Space Shower TV]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spaceshowertv.com/area/|title=SPACE SHOWER area|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130619154838/http://www.spaceshowertv.com/area/|archivedate=June 19, 2013}}</ref>\n| Program about music\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Catherine''\n| Herself / Host\n| [[Kansai TV]]\n| Japanese variety show\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''Catherine the Third''\n| Herself / Host\n| [[Kansai TV]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ktv.jp/catherine3/|title=Catherine 3|publisher=[[Kansai Telecasting Corporation]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130218164937/http://www.ktv.jp/catherine3/|archivedate=February 18, 2013}}</ref>\n| Japanese variety show\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Kazoku no Uta]]''\n| Herself\n| [[Fuji TV]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fujitv.co.jp/kazokunouta/index.html |title=Kazoku no Uta |publisher=[[Fuji Television|Fuji TV]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web